metadata.name: Skravert #7
metadata.description:
‚ÄòSkravert‚Äô - Norwegian, verb, past tense. ‚ÄòThe act of filling an area with lines; to shade an area‚Äô.

Skravert is a series of 320 sketches, each capturing the texture and feel of a material residing somewhere between cardboard and woolen rugs. The project is centred around rectangle subdivision and a line drawing algorithm, giving each piece its own unique expression when combined with a selection of 28 different color  palettes.  

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2021

metadata.name: Ocean #106
metadata.description:
Ocean is my second long-form generative work continuing my exploration of creating visual designs with polygons. As found with the name, Ocean, this piece is inspired by patterns of ocean waves, storms, typhoons, and urchins. Ocean is composed of six layout variations and four color palettes with a few singular inspirations.

metadata.name: Learning to Draw #50
metadata.description:
It's a collaboration between the computer and me. I tried to teach them to draw like a human artist, with all the imperfection that it means, and they tried to teach me to draw as a computer artist, with all the perfection that it means. The result is a cluster of approximative dots, jiggly lines and perfect bubbles, highlighted by colors carefully selected by them and me, after a long night of review, arguing and drinking red wine.

This is both of us, learning to draw.

PS: If any wanted or unwanted bug is found in an iteration, consider it as a blessing from the Genart Gods

Cheat codes:
* Press 1-8 to change resolution (or add &res=x to the url)
* Press s to save a PNG (or add &s=1 to the url)

metadata.name: Quadz #54
metadata.description:
Quadz is my first fxhash project which continues my exploration of creating visual designs based on polygons. Fxhash allowed me to develop a new take on the theme by generating polygon patterns based on rule-based randomization and p5js quad polygons. 

Quadz is composed of five layouts and three color palettes.

metadata.name: GRAPHEME #36
metadata.description:
Released on the occasion of the Tribute to Herbert W. Franke. 
www.tribute-hwf.com

‚ÄúOne criterion for art involves the process used by the artist for shaping the work. In the special case of mathematically supported fine art, the artmaking process occurs in a mathematically defined operation that allows the generation and transformation of images, methods used for picture processing.‚Äù - Herbert W. Franke

I first came across Franke‚Äôs ‚ÄòOrnamental Alphabets‚Äô in his book ùòäùò∞ùòÆùò±ùò∂ùòµùò¶ùò≥ ùòéùò≥ùò¢ùò±ùò©ùò™ùò§ùò¥ - ùòäùò∞ùòÆùò±ùò∂ùòµùò¶ùò≥ ùòàùò≥ùòµ, and was intrigued with the idea of using a simple letterform to explore different generative image processing techniques. 

I‚Äôve used letters and writing in my work for a long time, both with letterpress printing and in my asemic poetry programs. With asemic writing, I generate unrecognizable letters to reference text, and here I use recognizable letterforms removed from their typical function as language signifiers. 

My goal with this project was to build as much texture and layering as possible by warping and collaging the letters together in various ways. The font I‚Äôm using is a design I made years ago to supplement my wood type collection for printing. I really enjoyed being able to bring that part of my past work into my generative art practice. 

Each image is composed of the letters found in the hash for that piece, divided into either vowels or consonants. The program builds on a technique I‚Äôve used before, where I generate an image to an off-screen canvas and then dive through the pixels to pull out the color and form I want to surface in the final image.

25% of the primary sales will be donated on-chain to the Foundation Herbert W. Franke. These funds will be used by ZKM Karlsruhe to digitize Franke‚Äôs 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. Any additional funds raised will be donated to the R√ºtgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.

- Press ‚ÄúR‚Äù to increase the pixel density and reload the image (this can be render intensive and will create a really large file suitable for printing)
- Press ‚ÄúS‚Äù to save a copy

Made with p5js
Artist: Sarah Ridgley
October, 2022

metadata.name: Doodle Tiles v1.0 #27
metadata.description:
Diving into the 2D art scene with my first tile project. Varying hues and color values and creating a chaotic pattern on adjacent tiles but not as exact copies or alignments. Stretched and skewed, I sat here and went through literally hundreds of variations to make sure that I was pleased with the generation code.

Key presses will allow higher resolution rendering than your screen can show, as a multiple of the screen dimensions (this can take a lot of time at high multiples) and saving of the high-res image to your local disk in jpg or png format:

1: render at 2x screen resolution
2: render at 4x screen resolution
3: render at 8x screen resolution
4: render at 16x screen resolution (this takes many minutes)
(default is 1x screen resolution)

At whatever resolution you select above (including the default) press:
s: to save current rendering to "Doodle_Tiles.png"
S: to save current rendering to "Doodle_Tiles.jpg"

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #410
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. ‚ÄúThe Bugged Tree‚Äù‚Äôs code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren‚Äôt under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there‚Äôs a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan
